Scrape the Location Counts

# When Scraping the information from menuism.com, the process is the same, create a function is more efficient
scrape <- function(url){
  
  link <- read_html(url)
  data <- link %>% 
    html_nodes('.col-sm-6') %>% 
    html_nodes('a') %>% 
    html_text() %>% 
    as.data.frame()
  
  colnames(data) <- c('info')
  return (data)
}

This function stateabb() takes a state name (assume its spelled correctly) and converts it to its state abbreviation.

stateabb <- function(one_state){

  # Manually fix for state Virginia 
  if (one_state == "Virginia"){
    return ("VA")}
  if (one_state == "District of Columbia"){
    return ("DC")
  }
  # Locate the index of the state
  state_index <- grep(one_state, state.name)
  
  # Access the state abbreviation with the index
  state_result <- state.abb[state_index]
  
  return (state_result)
}

Parse, merge and tidy your data so that you have a row for each state and two columns: state abbrevation, location count.

extract_state <- function(string, store){
  pattern <- glue('.+?(?= ','{store}',')')
  result <- str_extract(string, pattern)
  return (result)
}


extract_count <- function(string){
  # Extract Count
  count = str_extract_all(string, "[0-9]") %>% 
  unlist() %>% paste0(collapse = '')
  return (as.integer(count))
}

# Create a function to combine both state and count 
cleanup <- function(data, store){
  state = map_chr(data, function(x) extract_state(x, store))
  count = map_int(data, function(x) extract_count(x))
  # Combine state and count into a dataframe
  final_data = data.frame(state, count)
  return (final_data)
}

Scrape State Population as Supplemental Data

Scrape the state names and populations from this wikipedia page. Convert the state names to abbreviations and merge these data with your coffee dataset.

wiki_url <- "https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_U.S._states_by_population"
wiki_html <- read_html(wiki_url)
wiki_orig <- wiki_html %>% html_nodes('table') %>% html_table()
wiki_data <- wiki_orig[[1]]
# Only need state and population
wiki <- wiki_data %>% select(c(3,4))

# Rename the colume 
colnames(wiki) <- c("state", "population")

# Remove non state
wiki <- wiki %>% filter(state %in% state.name) %>% as.data.frame()

# Abbreviate the states and update wiki 
state_abbreviation <- sapply(wiki$state, stateabb) %>% unname()
wiki$state <- state_abbreviation
# Remove the comma in Population and Convert it into numeric value 
remove_punc <- function(str){
  my_str <- str_remove_all(str, '\\,')
  return (as.integer(my_str))
}

# Covert populaton to numeric
population <- sapply(wiki$population, remove_punc) %>% unname()
wiki$population <- population

# Add District of Columnia in wiki dataframe
DC <- data.frame(state='DC', population = 701974)
wiki <- rbind(wiki, DC)

Create a region variable: Northeast, Midwest, South, West.

state_reg <- function(state_abbre){
  
  west <- c('CA', 'WA', 'OR', 'ID', 'MT', 'WY', 'NV', 'UT', 'CO', 
            'AZ', 'NM', 'AK', 'HI')
  midwest <- c('ND', 'SD', 'NE', 'KS', 'MN', 'IA',
               'MO', 'WI', 'IL', 'IN', 'MI', 'OH')
  south <- c('TX', 'OK', 'AR', 'LA', 'MS', 'TN', 'KY', 'WV', 
             'MD', 'DE', 'DC', 'VA', 'NC', 'SC', 'GA', 'FL', 'AL')
  northeast <- c('PA', 'NJ', 'NY', 'MA', 'CT', 'RI', 'VT', 'NH', 'ME', 'DC')

  if (state_abbre %in% west ){
    return ('West')
  } else if (state_abbre %in% midwest){
    return ('Midwest')
  } else if (state_abbre %in% south){
    return ('South')
  } else{ # if (state_abbre %in% northeast){
    return ('Northeast')
  }
}
region <- sapply(dataset2$state, state_reg) %>% unlist() %>% unname()
dataset2$region <- region

C. Do the financial data match what youd expect based on the number and locations of the stores? Why or why not?

  summarise(total_count = sum(count), revenue = mean(revenue)) %>% 
  
  ggplot(aes(x= total_count, y= revenue, color = company)) +

Note that Starbuck and Mcdonalds have many more locations than other coffee companies thus I expect to see a high revenue just as the graph shows while a lower number of locations corresponds to a low revenue.
